# Fluff Date: 2026-02-26 19:50:04
overview:<p>The Guillotine IIC is a Clan-technology rebuild of the venerable Inner Sphere Guillotine, developed by Clan Coyote engineers during the Golden Century as part of the Clans' broader effort to upgrade the Star League-era designs they had carried into exile. Officially unveiled in 2889, the design replaced the original Inner Sphere chassis with a Clan endo steel frame and upgraded the weapons suite entirely with Clan-manufactured equivalents, transforming the dependable raider into a considerably more lethal second-line combatant. Although Clan Coyote created the design, Clan Star Adder was the first to employ it in combat.</p><p>Production at the Omega Orbital Production Plant on Babylon continued through the Clan Invasion era, after which the Guillotine IIC largely faded from production. The design saw a resurgence during the Jihad when Clan Wolf established refit facilities on Weingarten to convert salvaged Inner Sphere Guillotine chassis into IIC-standard machines, and later when the Wolves captured Angell II and converted the Irian BattleMechs Unlimited factory there to produce new Guillotine IICs for their rebuilding forces.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Guillotine IIC retains the original design's twelve tons of Forging OTR17b armor, speed profile, and jump capability while substantially upgrading its offensive potential through Clan technology. The primary weapon is a Clan Mk. XVII extended-range PPC that provides fearsome long-range striking power, while the arm-mounted medium lasers are replaced with a pair of Kolibri Delta Series large pulse lasers that deliver devastating accuracy at closer ranges. Two Series 2f ER medium lasers and a Clan Series 4d SRM-6 round out the weapons suite, providing flexible engagement options across all range bands.</p><p>Sixteen Clan double heat sinks manage the substantially increased thermal load, though aggressive use of the full weapons suite can still push the design into dangerous heat territory. The Clan Modified Heavy Type X endo steel chassis provides the same weight savings as the original Crucis-I frame while using fewer critical slots, and four Clan Series Type 4 heavy jump jets maintain the 120-meter jump distance that made the original Guillotine such an effective raider. The net result is a 'Mech that hits significantly harder than its Inner Sphere ancestor at all ranges while maintaining the same survivability and mobility that defined the original design.</p>

deployment:<p>The standard Guillotine IIC carries the full Clan weapons upgrade centered on a Clan Mk. XVII ER PPC, paired Kolibri Delta Series large pulse lasers, two Series 2f ER medium lasers, and a Clan Series 4d SRM-6 with a single ton of ammunition. Sixteen double heat sinks and four Clan heavy jump jets round out the configuration. This standard model was the primary production variant from the Omega Orbital Production Plant on Babylon and was subsequently produced or converted at facilities on Weingarten and Angell II. Primarily assigned to second-line and solahma units, in Clan Coyote a Star Captain or Trinary Commander would typically be assigned to pilot this machine.</p>

history:<p>The Exodus fleet carried a large number of Guillotines away from the Inner Sphere as part of General Kerensky's forces. When the Clans formed and began building their military from existing designs, substantial stocks of Guillotines were found in storage on the Pentagon Worlds of Eden and Circe and distributed among the various Clans. These original machines served on the front lines until the advent of the OmniMech rendered them obsolete for first-line duty, at which point they were relegated to second-line and solahma formations.</p><p>Clan Coyote undertook the redesign that produced the Guillotine IIC, applying Clan technology to create a more capable second-line machine rather than designing an entirely new 'Mech. The upgraded design was officially unveiled in 2889, and Clan Star Adder won several examples in a Trial of Possession, becoming the first Clan to take the new variant into combat. In 2892, Star Adder warriors deployed their Guillotine IICs against a Clan Mongoose raiding force that was seeking genetic material from the Adders' homeworld. The resulting five-hour battle proved the IIC's worth, with the timely arrival of two Stars composed entirely of Guillotine IICs turning the engagement decisively in the Star Adders' favor.</p><p>By the time of the Clan Invasion, Clans Star Adder, Cloud Cobra, and Coyote fielded the largest numbers of Guillotine IICs, with most other Clans maintaining smaller quantities for their garrison forces. Production at the Omega Orbital Production Plant eventually wound down as newer designs became available. The design experienced a revival during the Jihad when Clan Wolf, cut off from the Homeworld supply chains by the Word of Blake's disruption of interstellar commerce, established refit facilities on Weingarten to convert purchased or salvaged Inner Sphere Guillotines into IIC-standard machines. This expedient measure drew on Golden Century traditions of making do with available materials. Clan Wolf in Exile separately established their own conversion program on Arc-Royal. After Clan Wolf's participation in Operation HAMMERFALL and the establishment of the Wolf Empire, they captured Angell II and converted its Irian BattleMechs Unlimited production line to manufacture new Guillotine IICs, ensuring the design's continued availability into the ilClan era.</p>

manufacturer:Omega Orbital Production Plant, Irian BattleMechs Unlimited, W-7 Facilities

